en.description:
An Open Source Program Office (OSPO) is a dedicated unit within a company or organization responsible for managing collaboration involving open source software. Whether structured as a physical office or a virtual, task-oriented team, the core function of an OSPO is to oversee the adoption, distribution, and legal compliance of open source software. Its role extends beyond internal “use” of open source—it also promotes active external “participation” in open source communities to strengthen collaboration and ensure compliance across the software supply chain.

Although the concept of an OSPO has become increasingly well-defined, its implementation must still be tailored to each organization’s size, R&D structure, and cultural context. There is no one-size-fits-all model; OSPO planning and operations should be adapted to specific internal needs and practical constraints.

This talk draws on hands-on experience assisting Taiwanese companies in establishing OSPOs and will outline four key legal and governance considerations for effective open source management:

1. Establishing and maintaining version control systems (Version Control Systems, VCS);
2. Defining Approval and Rejection Lists in open source policies;
3. Developing clear guidelines and review procedures for upstream contributions;
4. Understanding and addressing the compliance implications of Copyleft license terms.
